r their newborn died near Louisville — a double loss before the mission was even reached."},{"number":2,"category":"religion","header":"He married two missionary widows in turn","body":"Widowed on the trail, Samuel married Mary Hunt McCarty at Harmony Mission in 1822, the widow of fellow missionary John Seeley. After Mary died in 1835 he married a third missionary widow, Sophia Palmer Joslyn, whose first husband had also died in the field."},{"number":3,"category":"migration","header":"The first Protestant to settle San Antonio","body":"After missions to the Osage and Cherokee, Samuel brought his family to San Antonio in 1848, when the town had scarcely a shingled roof among its adobe houses. Family record holds he was the first Protestant to settle there permanently; he opened a private school and helped found the city’s First Presbyterian Church."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"Six generations of Samuels before him","body":"Rev. Samuel Newton was the sixth Samuel Newton in unbroken succession — Samuel son of Samuel son of Samuel, back six generations to the immigrant minister Roger Newton. He carried that Connecticut lineage from a Woodbridge parsonage to the Texas frontier."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"X02122","link_text":"Ainsworth Blunt","display_label":"served the same Cherokee mission field in Indian Territory"}],"slug":"samuel-newton-1792"},"HD6474":{"id":"HD6474","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_thomas":9},"bio":{"display_name":"Col. Samuel Galitzin Newton","first_name":"Samuel Galitzin","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[],"title":"Col.","bio_blurb":"Lawyer, Confederate officer, and San Antonio mayor"},"birth":{"year":1823,"date_precision":"exact","month":3,"day":21,"city":"Bates County","state":"Missouri","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1874,"date_precision":"exact","month":6,"day":21,"city":"San Antonio","stat